In the first nine months of 2021, China was the UK's largest import source country, with the bilateral trade volume reaching over $80 billion. However, the UK government seems not satisfied with this. Britain's Foreign Secretary said that Chinese companies should not be involved in the construction of the UK's nuclear power plants. A few days earlier, Prime Minister Boris Johnson said in an interview that he did not want ministers to "pitchfork away" Chinese investment. Why are British politicians showing two diverging attitudes towards Chinese companies? In this episode of BizBeat, CGTN's Zheng Junfeng explains.